<h1 class="hero-h">AI agents for business: <em>what they are, what works, what doesn't.</em></h1>
<p class="hero-sub">'AI agents' is the most loaded term in B2B AI right now. Vendors call everything an agent. Definitions are slippery. Most coverage either oversells (agents will replace your team) or underdelivers (agents are just chatbots). This is the honest 2026 breakdown — what they are, which platforms work, and the use cases that consistently produce value.</p>
<div class="verdict"><div class="verdict-l">The short version</div><p class="verdict-p">An AI agent is software that can plan, take actions across multiple tools, remember context across sessions, and self-correct when something goes wrong. Most products labeled 'agent' in 2026 are actually workflows with LLM steps — useful but not the same. Real agents (Claude Skills, sophisticated Lindy setups, custom code) shine on multi-step tasks with structured outputs: research synthesis, scheduled reporting, document workflows, lifecycle automation. They don't yet shine on judgment-heavy work, ambiguous decisions, or anything customer-facing without a review layer.</p></div>
</div></div>

<div style="background:#0A1A0A;border-top:1px solid #1A3A1A;border-bottom:1px solid #1A3A1A;padding:1.25rem 2.5rem;">
